passages.text: NXT's FY25 result highlighted several positive developments, including the accelerated billing of the forward order book driven by AI, a JV partnership for NXT's first Japan data center, and progress towards setting up a JV structure for NXT's hyperscale S4 and S7 facilities. The FY25 result and guidance for FY26 were broadly in- line with JPME and consensus, whilst the pull forward of billing capacity drives upgrades to FY27 EBITDA. The company was also upbeat on the prospects of another record year of contract wins in FY26, which could drive billing from FY27/FY28+. NXT has appointed advisors to find a capital partner to build out S4 and S7, and in our view this materially de- risks a near- term capital raise as we see the business as being well funded for sites that are currently under construction. Near term, we see the pending approval of the S5 facility as a potential catalyst for the stock, with mgmt sounding confident on the call.

In- line result and guide, but accelerated billing drives FY27 upgrades. NXT reported an in- line FY25 result and provided FY26 guidance that was also broadly in- line with JPME and consensus. The company highlighted that its large forward order book (134MW) was now expected to bill earlier than previously expected, as these relate to AI deployments that convert much more quickly than traditional cloud workloads. This drives our FY27E EBITDA upgrade of \(+21\%\) to \(\sim\) 353m.

JV structures reduce capital raise NXT announced that they have appointed advisors to establish a JV for the development of the S4 and S7 data centres in Western Sydney. These two facilities are expected to deliver 850MW \(+\) of capacity to hyperscale clients, and NXT expects \(\sim\) 515bn of total funding required over \(10+\) years. NXT will hold a minority stake in the JV, whilst being responsible for the management and operations of the vehicle. This will unlock access to lower cost of capital and allow higher gearing, whilst NXT still retains an economic exposure. NXT is targeting initial financial close for the JV within the next 12- 18 months.

Robust balance sheet to support near- term capex needs. NXT upsized its debt facilities to \(\) 6.4b\(earlier in the month, and currently has\) \ \(5.5bn\) of liquidity available to deploy for near- term capex needs. The company's FY26 guidance for \(\) 1.8bn-\ \(2bn of capex sits comfortably under this limit. In our view, the likely scenario where NXT may need to tap equity markets again would be if there is an opportunity to accelerate development of a new facility (post S5 approval).

Maintain Overweight, PT increases to \(\) 19.50\(/sh. Our PT is driven by our Dec - 26 DCF - based valuation. NXT's forward order book underwrites growth into the next few years, and we expect further contract wins to help extend that runway. The company is also well placed to continue benefitting from the secular growth in data centre infrastructure. We've revised our earnings to reflect the new billing ramp, and our EBITDA over FY26E/FY27E increases by \(+1\% / + 21\%\) .
Sources for: Style Exposure - J.P. Morgan Global Markets Strategy; all other tables are company data and J.P. Morgan estimates.

With data centers in the five major capital cities, NextDC is one of the leading data- center operators in Australia and the only pure play on the Australian data- center market. With its first- generation data centers in Brisbane, Sydney and Melbourne completely sold out, and similar progress with its second- generation facilities, the company is rapidly scaling up by building larger and more dense facilities. We expect these facilities to generate a mid- to high- teens IRR as they fill and benefit from the strong demand from both hyperscalers and enterprise customers. We do see strong competition from incumbents, but note that NXT's differentiated model and broader presence across Australia are likely to present a point of difference.

Our Dec- 26 price target of A\$19.50 is based on a discounted cash flow that assumes a \(7.4\%\) WACC and a \(3.5\%\) perpetual growth rate. We derive our WACC estimate based on the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM), which assumes a 10- year risk- free rate of \(4.0\%\) , equity risk premium of \(5.0\%\) , beta of 1.00, D/D \(+E\) ratio of \(35\%\) , and tax rate of \(30\%\) .

FY26 outlook provided several positive announcementsNXT ended FY25 with record contract wins (+72MW y/y, +42% y/y), albeit with the result largely in- line with JPME given the company provided an update on billing utilisation in June. The FY25 result delivered several positive updates, including: 1) acceleration of AI deployment billing, 2) accelerated development pipeline, 3) plans for a JV structure for S4/S7 facilities, 4) secured a \(\sim 30\mathrm{MW}\) site in Tokyo (TK1, in partnership with CBRE to be completed FY30), and 5) provided FY26 guidance in- line with JPME/consensus.
Figure 1: Strong growth in Forward Order book MW
Source: Company data

The bringing forward of the order book will drive an acceleration in EBITDA growth for NXT into FY27 and FY28. The main constraint will be NXT's ability to deliver the capacity on time to its customers. We expect NXT to continue winning further contracts that will drive outer year growth from FY28 and beyond. Given the lag between winning a contract and conversion into EBITDA, we believe investors should assess NXT on a contracted EBITDA multiple basis for better comparables.
Figure 3: EBITDA to materially step up in FY27E A\\(m
Source: Company data, J.P. Morgan estimates

NXT ended FY25 with a forward order book (contracted utilisation less billing utilisation) of 134MW to be delivered over the next 3- 4 years. However, this update noted a step- up in the pace of conversion, now expecting \(\sim 57\mathrm{MW}\) billing in FY26 and \(\sim 58\mathrm{MW}\) billing in FY27. Importantly, while cloud deployments typically have a longer ramp- up profile from a lower starting base, AI deployments for large- scale training/inference have a faster speed to billing (as a result of the larger day one capacity deployment), which drives an increase to FY27 earnings.
Figure 2: AI is driving acceleration
Source: Company data

NXT has appointed advisors to set up a JV for its S4 and S7 facilities. The company gave a snapshot of what the structure could look like, with NXT taking a minority equity stake in the vehicle, including tipping in \(\sim\) 500m of land. S4 and S7 combined would likely cost \(\sim\) \$15bn of total funding, and the company believes a JV structure would allow more efficient deployment of capital through higher gearing and tapping pools of private capital.

NextDC (Overweight; Price Target: A\(19.50)

With data centers in the five major capital cities, NextDC is one of the leading data- center operators in Australia and the only pure play on the Australian data- center market. With its first- generation data centers in Brisbane, Sydney and Melbourne completely sold out, and similar progress with its second- generation facilities, the company is rapidly scaling up by building larger and more dense facilities. We expect these facilities to generate a mid- to high- teens IRR as they fill and benefit from the strong demand from both hyperscalers and enterprise customers. We do see strong competition from incumbents, but note that NXT's differentiated model and broader presence across Australia are likely to present a point of difference.

Our Dec- 26 price target of A\(19.50 is based on a discounted cash flow that assumes a 7.4% WACC and a 3.5% perpetual growth rate. We derive our WACC estimate based on the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM), which assumes a 10- year risk- free rate of 4.0%, equity risk premium of 5.0%, beta of 1.00, D/D+E ratio of 35%, and tax rate of 30%.

- A large portion of capacity at NextDC's second-generation data centers is aimed at satisfying demand from hyperscale cloud operators such as AWS, Microsoft Azure and Google. Should these operators decide they prefer to build and own their own data centers, it would threaten the business case for these large data centers.- Constrained supply, driven by construction risks.- As with NXT's S2 facility, we saw significant construction delays due to the complexity of building large and vertical data centres. Any construction delays could lead to a lack of available capacity to sell through.
Upside catalysts include:

- NextDC operates best-in-class facilities in the industry with high barriers to entry.- NextDC is the first data center operator in the world to achieve Tier IV certification by The Uptime Institute on its second-generation data centers without having a full \(2N + 1\) redundancy system. This allows NextDC not only to attract customers that require best-in-class data center facilities, but also to operate with a lower fixed-cost base than competitors.- Continued exponential growth in data and cloud computing remains a secular tailwind for data centers.- While NextDC has been able to ride the remarkable \(20\% +\) CAGR of cloud computing, IT outsourcing and data usage growth over the last five years, we do not expect exponential growth to slow anytime soon. Cisco estimates high-teens growth in cloud computing globally, while Internet traffic and data usage continue to grow at \(20\% +\) annually.- We estimate a mid-to-high-teens IRR on second-generation data centers.- NextDC has achieved a low- to mid-\(20\%\) IRR on its first-generation data centers in Sydney, Melbourne and Brisbane. With capacity selling out within five to seven years and continued growth in Interconnectivity revenues, the company has proven its expertise in building out top-tier data centers and is able to attract a strong ecosystem of telecom vendors and partners. We estimate that the second-generation data centers will achieve mid- to high-teens returns despite being many times larger. These are favourable returns compared to its WACC of \(7.4\%\) .- Global expansion by large data center operators could drive industry M&A.- As the recent acquisitions of Metronode by Equinix, Ascenty by Digital Realty, Zenium by CyrusOne and CyrusOne's strategic partnership with GDS Holdings show, US-based data center operators are looking to expand internationally in order to meet customer demand. With long lead times for construction and difficulty securing prime real estate in metros, it makes more sense for these operators to acquire data centers than to build them themselves, in our view. This is particularly true if the data centers are recently built and are up to the highest standards, like those of NextDC.
